The best products feel obvious in retrospect, but what's invisible is the long meandering path to discover it in the first place.

Building new products is like playing Wordle except with the entire Unicode 150k character set and you're trying to invent a new word no one's heard of.

Hitting just one yellow square is a huge accomplishment.   Once you hit two yellow squares, you're 95% of the way to success.

If you've had a series of products that didn't work, try to look back to see if you missed any yellow squares—elements that showed high engagement from users but the product didn't work.

Once you've assembled a few yellow squares, string them in different combinations and try sounding out the word.

In life, there's no 6 guess limit.  Once you figured out the word, all your past failed attempts magically disappear. You appear a genius.
What's even more silly is even if you explicitly try to talk about your failed attempts, people will ignore it and focus on your win.

So be fearless.  Type "Fuzzy" (one of the worst starting words in Wordle).  Type z̶̨̧͙̝̼̙͕͗́́̓̓́̚ͅà̶̧̼͖̠̙̱͙̠̖̗̮͍̓̔̑̓.  Type 🍆🚀⛄.  Trace along the curvatures of your life to type in a word only you could think of because there's only one you.
Watch out for those yellow squares and know that if you've found two, you're just a few iterations away from something amazing.   Make sure to ping  when you do!

I’m hopeful that channels ensure high signal persists even with Farcaster’s version of “Eternal September”

Some reasonable routes seem to be: 

1. Raising higher walls between channels which stops the bleed between the types of content at the cost of channel discoverability.

2. Publish some kind of metric that lends to the nature of posts in the channel.  (i.e. Do most posts fill up with content? Is there signal?)

3. Implement a form of AI moderation that stops the most egregious, low signal users.  Though this treads the line of “what makes good content?”

4. Take a longer term route at trying to instill strong social norms through social feedback from o.g. users.

It’s a tough problem to crack.  It’s unfortunately been a problem since the Usenet days of “Eternal September” where a sudden influx of users overwhelm the social norms established by veteran members.
Great point! I agree, giving channel operators effective ways to strengthen social norms in a scalable way would lift FC quality for all of us.

The only way you succeed building something new is to build something that’s you.

Whew! This was a lesson that even the simplest frame actions can compound with complexity when you start dealing with pairs of people interacting.

A large number of edge cases that have to be remedied.  Multiplayer frames development is a very different beast compared to single player product dev.

Hard lesson learned on coding multiplayer frame interfaces.  It’s a very unusual product surface where multiple people can interact with the same button with different contexts.

Purely digital consumer products are emotion machines.  You feed it with your attention or money, you get an emotional return.  The technology that's innovating on this aspect is improving on these axes:

1. Asymmetric returns in emotional potency.  Small(er) investment needed than ever before for outsized results.

2. Novelty of feeling.  Applications that can engender different parts of the human condition that previously were not digitally reproducible.

3. Consistency.  This feels contradictory to #2, but applications that can consistently deliver fresh, pleasurable emotions is king.

The four fundamental building blocks that make the new paradigm possible are:

1. Crypto.  You can now wield financial incentives with previously impossible payout structures designed to enhance the three axes above.  There is no limit to the degree of complexity for each transaction.
2. AI.  It is now possible for extraordinarily small teams to leverage a vast amount creative output as ingredients in servicing novel emotions for its users.

3. Mobile.  This was the earliest key breakthrough that we regard today as "old news", but the fact that we all have a personal, always online, interface that can provide push notifications is in the bedrock of this paradigm.

4. Cloud.  As  referenced, these are infinitely scalable robots able to do anyone's bidding that are stored in Amazon datacenters for energy efficiency.  It is here where consumer digital products gain their asymmetric upside where a $100 a month server can service tens of thousands of users.

My expectations are we'll see an explosion of small teams (<10) that are incredibly highly levered, producing apps that produce novel emotion that transact previously unimaginable scale of volume thought to only belong to AAA gaming studios employing hundreds to thousands of people.
Our efforts at  is a culmination of these trends coming together into a magical product that delights, providing an enormous amount of novel joy to the world.
